<p><i><b>Nix v. Hedden</b>,</i> <a href="/wiki/Case_citation" title="Case citation">149 U.S. 304</a> (<a href="/wiki/1893" title="1893">1893</a>)<span class="reference plainlinksneverexpand" id="ref_citation"><sup><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nix_v._Hedden#endnote_citation" class="external autonumber" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nix_v._Hedden#endnote_citation" rel="nofollow">[1]</a></sup></span>, was a case in which the <a href="/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title="Supreme Court of the United States">United States Supreme Court</a> addressed whether a <a href="/wiki/Tomato" title="Tomato">tomato</a> was classified as a <a href="/wiki/Fruit" title="Fruit">fruit</a> or a <a href="/wiki/Vegetable" title="Vegetable">vegetable</a> under the <a href="/wiki/Tariff" title="Tariff">Tariff</a> Act of March 3, 1883, which required a tax to be paid on imported vegetables, but not fruit. The case was filed as an action by John Nix, John W. Nix, George W. Nix, and Frank W. Nix against <a href="/w/index.php?title=Edward_L._Hedden&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Edward L. Hedden (page does not exist)">Edward L. Hedden</a>, <a href="/wiki/Collector_of_the_Port_of_New_York" title="Collector of the Port of New York">Collector of the Port of New York</a>, to recover back duties paid under protest. <a href="/wiki/Botany" title="Botany">Botanically</a> a tomato is a fruit. The court, however, unanimously ruled in favor of the defendant, that the Tariff Act used the ordinary meaning of the words "fruit" and "vegetable" - where a tomato is classified as a vegetable - not the technical botanical meaning.</p>
